---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Underwriting Rule Engine — Igor Bielov">
  <Nav showBack />

  <div class="case-page">

    <!-- ── HERO: two-column layout ──────────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="hero-section">

      <!-- Left column (35%): project identity -->
      <div class="hero-left">

        <!-- 1. Title -->
        <h1 class="panel-title">Underwriting Rule Engine</h1>

        <!-- 2. Description -->
        <p class="panel-description">No-code platform for risk managers to build and manage loan approval logic without engineering.</p>

        <!-- 3. Divider -->
        <div class="panel-divider"></div>

        <!-- 4. Metadata blocks -->
        <div class="panel-meta-group">
          <div class="panel-meta-block">
            <span class="panel-meta-label">Domain</span>
            <span class="panel-meta-value">Fintech · B2B SaaS</span>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-meta-block">
            <span class="panel-meta-label">Stage</span>
            <span class="panel-meta-value">0→1</span>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-meta-block">
            <span class="panel-meta-label">Role</span>
            <span class="panel-meta-value">Solo Designer</span>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-meta-block">
            <span class="panel-meta-label">Scope</span>
            <span class="panel-meta-value">Full system — canvas, objects, design system</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 5. Divider -->
        <div class="panel-divider"></div>

        <!-- 6. THE PROBLEM block -->
        <div class="panel-info-block">
          <span class="panel-info-label">The Problem</span>
          <p class="panel-info-body">Every loan approval or rejection runs through a rule a risk manager wrote. A wrong rule doesn't create a support ticket — it means real people get incorrect decisions on their applications. The product needed to put that logic in the hands of the people responsible for it, without requiring engineering every time something had to change.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- 7. Divider -->
        <div class="panel-divider"></div>

        <!-- 8. THE USER block -->
        <div class="panel-info-block">
          <span class="panel-info-label">The User</span>
          <p class="panel-info-body">Finance professionals, not engineers. They work from business logic — conditions and outcomes. They need certainty before they act. Their mistakes aren't caught in testing. They're caught on a real application, after the fact.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Right column (65%): hero screenshot -->
      <div class="hero-right">
        <div class="hero-frame">
          <img
            class="hero-image"
            src="/assets/cases/ure/hero-canvas-light.png"
            alt="Underwriting Rule Engine — redesigned canvas"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="hero-toggle">
          <button class="hero-toggle-btn active" data-mode="light">
            <svg class="hero-toggle-icon" width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/>
              <path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/>
            </svg>
            Light
          </button>
          <button class="hero-toggle-btn" data-mode="dark">
            <svg class="hero-toggle-icon" width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M21 12.79A9 9 0 1 1 11.21 3 7 7 0 0 0 21 12.79z"/>
            </svg>
            Dark
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

      <!-- ── SECTION 00 · WHAT WASN'T WORKING ───────────────────── -->
      <section class="case-section s00">

        <div class="s00-label">00 · WHAT WASN'T WORKING</div>

        <div class="s00-cards">

          <div class="s00-card">
            <span class="s00-card-index">01</span>
            <div class="s00-card-rule"></div>
            <h3 class="s00-card-title">Navigation without hierarchy</h3>
            <p class="s00-card-body">Everything in one list — active work, reference tools, settings, primary actions. No hierarchy, no separation. The user had to scan everything just to orient themselves before starting.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="s00-card">
            <span class="s00-card-index">02</span>
            <div class="s00-card-rule"></div>
            <h3 class="s00-card-title">Objects without feedback</h3>
            <p class="s00-card-body">No validation before committing. No summary of what you configured. If two conditions contradicted each other, nothing flagged it — the rule just ran wrong on real applications.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="s00-card">
            <span class="s00-card-index">03</span>
            <div class="s00-card-rule"></div>
            <h3 class="s00-card-title">Outdated component library &amp; UI</h3>
            <p class="s00-card-body">The visual direction was strictly defined by the client — heavy icons, colored action bars, dense layout. The component library had no dark mode and no shared token system, so every new screen required manual styling decisions. The result looked like a generic enterprise admin panel.</p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="s00-problem">
          <div class="s00-problem-header">
            <svg class="s00-problem-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
              <path d="M4 4L8 8M8 4L4 8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <span class="s00-problem-label">PROBLEM</span>
          </div>
          <p class="s00-problem-body">The original was built fast under real constraints. After shipping I had distance I didn't have during the build. Three problems — not UI issues, but trust failures in a system where a wrong rule reaches real people.</p>
          <p class="s00-problem-body">The first problem drove the Canvas redesign. The second drove the Decision Table redesign. The third — a visual language strictly dictated by the client — is what the full rebuild addressed.</p>
          <p class="s00-problem-body">Across all three — the goal was the same: give users visibility and control over their actions before those actions affect live business flows.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="s00-expandable">
          <button class="s00-toggle" aria-expanded="false">+ WHY THE VISUAL LANGUAGE CHANGED</button>
          <div class="s00-expand-body" hidden>
            <p class="s00-expand-text">The original UI was built on an MUI base with explicit client requirements: the visual direction was windows-like — heavy icons, colored action bars, dense component styling. For a precision tool used by finance professionals making high-stakes decisions, that visual language creates the wrong cognitive context. It signals a generic enterprise dashboard, not a system built for focused, careful work.</p>
            <p class="s00-expand-text">The redesign used Linear as the reference point. Linear is a complex system used by people who need to move fast and trust what they're looking at. Its visual language — minimal chrome, clear hierarchy, nothing competing with the content — is what makes it feel like a precision tool rather than a form-filling interface. That's the direction the redesign follows: strip everything that isn't earning its visual weight, and let the structure of the information do the work.</p>
            <p class="s00-expand-text">The result is a dramatic visual shift from the original. That shift wasn't arbitrary — it was a deliberate correction of a UI language that was working against the user.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- ── SECTION 01 · CANVAS ─────────────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="case-section s01">

        <div class="s01-label">01 · CANVAS</div>

        <!-- Before/After visual pair -->
        <div class="s01-pair">

          <!-- BEFORE frame -->
          <div class="s01-frame">
            <img
              class="s01-frame-img"
              src="/assets/cases/ure/canvas-before.png"
              alt="Canvas sidebar — before redesign"
            />
            <div class="s01-frame-caption s01-frame-caption--problem">
              <div class="s01-frame-caption-header">
                <svg class="s01-frame-caption-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                  <path d="M4 4L8 8M8 4L4 8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
                <span class="s01-frame-caption-title">Problem</span>
              </div>
              <p class="s01-frame-caption-body">Two different user modes collapsed into one list — active work and occasional reference, no hierarchy between them. Before touching anything, the user had to figure out where they were.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- AFTER frame -->
          <div class="s01-frame s01-after-frame">
            <img
              class="s01-after-img"
              src="/assets/cases/ure/canvas-after-light.png"
              alt="Canvas sidebar — after redesign"
            />
            <div class="s01-frame-caption s01-frame-caption--solution">
              <div class="s01-frame-caption-header">
                <svg class="s01-frame-caption-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                  <path d="M3.5 6L5.5 8L8.5 4.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
                <span class="s01-frame-caption-title">Solution</span>
              </div>
              <p class="s01-frame-caption-body">The sidebar is now split into two explicit zones — flows at the top, global platform features at the bottom. Each zone has a clear label.</p>
              <div class="s01-img-toggle">
                <button class="s01-img-toggle-btn active" data-mode="light">
                  <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/>
                    <path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/>
                  </svg>
                  Light
                </button>
                <button class="s01-img-toggle-btn" data-mode="dark">
                  <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <path d="M21 12.79A9 9 0 1 1 11.21 3 7 7 0 0 0 21 12.79z"/>
                  </svg>
                  Dark
                </button>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>


        <!-- Summary text -->
        <div class="s01-expand-subhead" style="max-width:640px;margin:32px auto 0;">THE OUTCOME</div>
        <p class="s01-summary-text" style="margin-top:12px;">Primary work context and system-level tools are now in separate labeled zones. The user sees what they need for the current task immediately. Navigation is organized by how each part is used, not just listed by what it is.</p>

        <!-- Expandable -->
        <div class="s01-expandable">
          <button class="s01-exp-toggle" aria-expanded="false">+ FULL REASONING</button>
          <div class="s01-expand-body" hidden>
            <div class="s01-expand-subhead">THE PROPOSED FIX AND BLOCKERS</div>
            <p class="s01-expand-text">The most direct fix was moving platform utilities into the header — global tools belong in global navigation. The client refused because other products in the portfolio used the header for system-wide notifications (Follow-ups, Comments, Alerts), and they wanted consistency across all eight products. But Underwriting had none of those features planned even in post-MVP state, we couldn't reach agreement.</p>
            <div class="s01-expand-subhead">THE REDESIGN</div>
            <p class="s01-expand-text">Rather than fight a blocked path, the redesign introduces two explicit zones within the sidebar itself. Flow states sit at the top — Production Flow, Draft Flows, the active flow tree. Platform tools anchor to the bottom under a PLATFORM label. The pattern exists in Figma, Linear, and VS Code for the same reason: active work and occasional reference are different modes, and the sidebar reflects that.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- ── SECTION 02 · CANVAS (COPY) ───────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="case-section s02">

        <div class="s02-label">02 · OBJECT (DECISION TABLE)</div>

        <!-- Before/After visual pair -->
        <div class="s02-pair">

          <!-- BEFORE frame -->
          <div class="s02-frame">
            <img
              class="s02-frame-img"
              src="/assets/cases/ure/canvas-before.png"
              alt="Canvas sidebar — before redesign"
            />
            <div class="s02-frame-caption s02-frame-caption--problem">
              <div class="s02-frame-caption-header">
                <svg class="s02-frame-caption-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                  <path d="M4 4L8 8M8 4L4 8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
                <span class="s02-frame-caption-title">Problem</span>
              </div>
              <p class="s02-frame-caption-body">No way to verify work before committing it. You configured the logic, hit Save, and it was live. Wrong rules reached real applications.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- AFTER frame -->
          <div class="s02-frame s02-after-frame">
            <img
              class="s02-after-img"
              src="/assets/cases/ure/canvas-after-light.png"
              alt="Canvas sidebar — after redesign"
            />
            <div class="s02-frame-caption s02-frame-caption--solution">
              <div class="s02-frame-caption-header">
                <svg class="s02-frame-caption-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                  <path d="M3.5 6L5.5 8L8.5 4.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
                <span class="s02-frame-caption-title">Solution</span>
              </div>
              <p class="s02-frame-caption-body">Test Node, Rule Summary, Health Status — three additions that move the verification work from the user's head into the interface.</p>
              <div class="s02-img-toggle">
                <button class="s02-img-toggle-btn active" data-mode="light">
                  <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/>
                    <path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/>
                  </svg>
                  Light
                </button>
                <button class="s02-img-toggle-btn" data-mode="dark">
                  <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <path d="M21 12.79A9 9 0 1 1 11.21 3 7 7 0 0 0 21 12.79z"/>
                  </svg>
                  Dark
                </button>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>


        <!-- Summary text -->
        <div class="s02-expand-subhead" style="max-width:640px;margin:32px auto 0;color:var(--color-text-primary);">THE OUTCOME</div>
        <p class="s02-summary-text" style="margin-top:12px;">Three changes address the same gap. Test Node lets the user validate logic before committing it. Rule Summary shows a plain-language readback of what they configured, so they can verify it without reconstructing it from raw values. Health Status surfaces conflicts passively. The user can now finish configuring and know it's correct before it's live.</p>
        <p class="s02-summary-text" style="margin-top:12px;">Before these changes, the system trusted the user to catch their own mistakes. Now the interface carries that responsibility.</p>

        <div class="s02-expand-subhead" style="max-width:640px;margin:32px auto 0;color:var(--color-text-primary);">THREE CHANGES, ONE NEED: CONFIDENCE BEFORE ACTION</div>
        <p class="s02-summary-text" style="margin-top:12px;"><span class="s02-expand-term">Test Node</span> — Placed as a co-primary action next to Save, not buried in a menu. The point is that validation has to be as easy as saving, or it gets skipped.</p>

        <!-- Test Node image switcher -->
        <div class="dt-switcher">
          <div class="dt-switcher-frame">
            <img class="dt-switcher-img" src="/assets/cases/ure/DT-TestMode-Start-1.png" alt="Test Node state" />
          </div>
          <div class="dt-switcher-controls">
            <button class="dt-arrow dt-arrow-prev" aria-label="Previous state">
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                <polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <span class="dt-state-label" data-state="test">TEST MODE</span>
            <button class="dt-arrow dt-arrow-next" aria-label="Next state">
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                <polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="dt-switcher-theme-toggle">
              <button class="dt-theme-btn active" data-theme="light">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/>
                  <path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/>
                </svg>
                Light
              </button>
              <button class="dt-theme-btn" data-theme="dark">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <path d="M21 12.79A9 9 0 1 1 11.21 3 7 7 0 0 0 21 12.79z"/>
                </svg>
                Dark
              </button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="s02-summary-text" style="margin-top:24px;"><span class="s02-expand-term">Rule Summary</span> — A plain-language readback of the configured rule in the sidebar. Risk managers think in conditions and outcomes — the interface should speak that language back to them, not make them reconstruct it from table cells.</p>
        <p class="s02-summary-text" style="margin-top:12px;"><span class="s02-expand-term">Health Status</span> — System state surfaced passively. If something is broken or in conflict, it's visible without having to navigate away from the work.</p>

      </section>

      <!-- ── SECTION 03 · HOW OBJECTS ARE FILLED ─────────────────── -->
      <section class="case-section svf">

        <div class="svf-label">03 · HOW OBJECTS ARE FILLED</div>

        <!-- Screenshot frame -->
        <div class="svf-frame-wrap">
          <div class="svf-frame">
            <img
              class="svf-frame-img"
              src="/assets/cases/ure/VS-DataType-Variable-Light.png"
              alt="Variable data type selection — Condition Builder"
            />
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Light/Dark toggle -->
        <div class="svf-img-toggle">
          <button class="svf-img-toggle-btn active" data-mode="light">
            <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/>
              <path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/>
            </svg>
            Light
          </button>
          <button class="svf-img-toggle-btn" data-mode="dark">
            <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M21 12.79A9 9 0 1 1 11.21 3 7 7 0 0 0 21 12.79z"/>
            </svg>
            Dark
          </button>
        </div>

        <!-- Problem + Solution -->
        <div class="svf-summary">
          <div class="svf-summary-block">
            <div class="svf-summary-header svf-summary-header--problem">
              <svg class="svf-summary-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                <path d="M4 4L8 8M8 4L4 8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              </svg>
              <span class="svf-summary-label">PROBLEM</span>
            </div>
            <p class="svf-summary-body">Risk managers start from a business rules document — 100 or more rules written in plain language. Their job is to translate that into the system. The translation is the work, and the translation is where errors happen.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="svf-summary-block">
            <div class="svf-summary-header svf-summary-header--solution">
              <svg class="svf-summary-icon" width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                <circle cx="6" cy="6" r="5.5" stroke="currentColor"/>
                <path d="M3.5 6L5.5 8L8.5 4.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
              <span class="svf-summary-label">SOLUTION</span>
            </div>
            <p class="svf-summary-body">The Condition Builder now shows a live representation of the expression as the user builds it — before it's committed.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Expandable -->
        <div class="svf-expandable">
          <button class="svf-exp-toggle" aria-expanded="false">+ FULL REASONING</button>
          <div class="svf-expand-body" hidden>
            <p class="svf-expand-text">Risk managers don't start from a data schema. They start from a business rules document — a file that can have 100 or more rules, each written in plain language: "approve if credit score exceeds 700 and loan amount is under 50k." That's the simple case. Real rules reference historical data, cross-source flags, edge conditions built up over years of compliance work. Their job is to translate all of that into the system. The translation is the work, and the translation is where errors happen.</p>
            <p class="svf-expand-text">The Condition Builder is where that translation happens. Each condition is an expression: Main Variable → Operator → Value. The risk manager isn't configuring a database field — they're writing a sentence the system can execute. Source narrows the domain, Category narrows the context, Variable completes the expression. The breadcrumb at the bottom — Application › Credit › BankruptcyFlag — is the finished equation before it's committed.</p>
            <p class="svf-expand-text">This is what makes the product no-code. The risk manager works in the language they already use — conditions and outcomes — and the interface handles the mapping to the underlying data model.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- ── SECTION 04 · HOW IT WAS BUILT ───────────────────────── -->
      <section class="case-section s03">

        <div class="s03-label">04 · HOW IT WAS BUILT</div>

        <!-- Tool Chain Component -->
        <div class="s03-toolchain">

          <div class="s03-tool-card">
            <div class="s03-tool-card-inner">
              <img src="/assets/cases/ure/claude.png" alt="Claude" class="s03-tool-logo" />
              <ul class="s03-tool-list">
                <li>Planning</li>
                <li>Specs</li>
                <li>Audit</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="s03-tool-sep">+</div>

          <div class="s03-tool-card">
            <div class="s03-tool-card-inner">
              <img src="/assets/cases/ure/codex.png" alt="Codex" class="s03-tool-logo" />
              <ul class="s03-tool-list">
                <li>Execution</li>
                <li>Fixes</li>
                <li>Storybook</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="s03-tool-sep">+</div>

          <div class="s03-tool-card">
            <div class="s03-tool-card-inner">
              <img src="/assets/cases/ure/figma.png" alt="Figma" class="s03-tool-logo" />
              <ul class="s03-tool-list">
                <li>Figma MCP</li>
                <li>Manual Fixes</li>
                <li>Review</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <!-- Summary -->
        <div class="s03-summary">
          <div class="s03-summary-block">
            <span class="s03-summary-label">PROBLEM</span>
            <p class="s03-summary-body">I used AI tooling to rebuild a complex system I'd already shipped — solo. It worked, and it also failed in specific ways: 116 tokens unusable because I underinvested in structure upfront, credits burned in three days by choosing the wrong model for the wrong tasks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="s03-summary-block">
            <span class="s03-summary-label">RESULT</span>
            <p class="s03-summary-body">The three lessons here came from those failures, not from the parts that went right.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Expandable -->
        <div class="s03-expandable">
          <button class="s03-exp-toggle" aria-expanded="false">+ FULL REASONING</button>
          <div class="s03-expand-body" hidden>

            <p class="s03-expand-text">This redesign wasn't a client brief. I took a system I'd already shipped, waited until I had enough distance from it to see it clearly, and rebuilt it using AI tooling to handle the execution layer. That separation — AI running the mechanical work, me reviewing the output — kept me in the auditor's seat instead of the builder's seat. That's harder to maintain than it sounds when you're working alone.</p>
            <p class="s03-expand-text">The workflow was divided by what each tool does best. Claude handled planning, audit, and spec work — the analytical layer where structured thinking matters more than execution speed. Claude Code and Codex handled component generation and execution. Figma MCP kept design and implementation in sync throughout, eliminating the round-trips that normally fragment this kind of work.</p>
            <p class="s03-expand-text">Working this way created something genuinely hard to maintain in pure execution mode: critical distance. When the model handles the mechanical work, there's room to step back and audit decisions rather than just make them.</p>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="s03-expand-subhead">Three things I'd do differently</div>

        <!-- Reflection Cards -->
        <div class="s03-reflect-cards">

          <div class="s03-reflect-card">
            <span class="s03-reflect-index">01</span>
            <h3 class="s03-reflect-title">Plan the system before building it</h3>
            <p class="s03-reflect-body">I underinvested in design system structure upfront. The result was over 116 tokens that became unusable — more time spent fixing than building. The right ratio is closer to 80% planning, 20% execution. This applies to AI-assisted work more than traditional work: the model executes fast, which means structural mistakes compound fast.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="s03-reflect-card">
            <span class="s03-reflect-index">02</span>
            <h3 class="s03-reflect-title">Match the model to the task</h3>
            <p class="s03-reflect-body">I used Opus for tasks Sonnet handles equally well, which burned through the weekly token budget in three days. Choosing which model to use for which task is an operational decision that directly affects output. Treating it as a footnote is how you run out of credits midway through a complex system.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="s03-reflect-card">
            <span class="s03-reflect-index">03</span>
            <h3 class="s03-reflect-title">Structure the workflow before starting</h3>
            <p class="s03-reflect-body">I had the right tools — Claude, Claude Code, Figma MCP — but used them without a defined sequence on the first run. The knowledge is now structured. I know how to sequence the work before it begins, not reconstruct the workflow while it's in progress.</p>
          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

